text:
For all the people that can't pause fast enough, the review said:

Today I'm going to the lowest rated restaurant in my city and leaving a positive review. The only rule is that I can't lie. judging by the 1 star reviews and the police helicopter circling the restaurant, this is gonna be my hardest challenge yet.

At first glance, this place looks awesome. I walked and got seated by fastest woman I've ever seen I mean she's flying

My utensils didn't work, but I like eating with my hands, that's a star! Don't judge me.

This meal reminded me of childhood and getting bullied in the cafeteria

Say it with me THATS A STAR!!!

I paid for my lunch and took a fortune cookie. Right when I thought 5 stars was out of the picture, I opened the cookie...

text:
Bro I was asking about your beep test score. Let me explain:
The bleep or beep test is a multi-stage fitness test in which you must do 20 metre shuttle runs in time with the bleeps until the bleeps get too quick for you. It is a maximal test which means it will take you to your fitness limit. The shuttle runs are done in time to bleep sounds on a pre-recorded audio cassette.

text:
Three elements in this that push beyond the limits of normal entertainment :

1 - The concept of following the rules meshes perfectly and comedically with your character/personality IRL
2 - The metaphor of 100 days in the game (people say we have 100 years to live if healthy)
3 - You start off trying to do right, trying to live by the rules you've been told. Now you start to get older. You realize there is a time limit to this whole experience. You might not get what society tells you that you are to strive for, unless you do unsatisfactory things. Things that might change the "you" who wanted the life in the first place. You do it anyways. What is this life, unless you enjoy it after all? You, Ryan, as a person understand and empathize with the mindset of someone that has actually been in spots like this.

This is an absolute masterpiece of a video. Thank you for creating this.

text:
Im a guy so here is a tutioral on how land mines work

Introduction to Land Mines
Land mines are explosive devices designed with the primary purpose of deterring enemy movement or causing injury and damage. These devices have been used historically in warfare to secure perimeters, prevent access, and create strategic barriers. With varying types and mechanisms, the functionality and deployment of land mines are critical in understanding their impact and the challenges they present in both military and humanitarian contexts.

Components and Design
The basic structure of a land mine includes a casing, explosive charge, trigger mechanism, and detonator. The casing, often made of metal or plastic, conceals and protects the internal components. The explosive charge, such as TNT, provides the destructive power. The trigger mechanism can be activated by pressure, a tripwire, or proximity, depending on the mine's design. This mechanism initiates the detonator, which in turn activates the explosive charge. The combination of these components determines how effectively the mine functions in its intended environment.

Activation and Detonation
Land mines operate through a precise sequence of events leading to detonation. When a person or vehicle applies pressure or triggers the tripwire mechanism, the detonator is activated. The detonator then ignites the explosive charge, resulting in an explosion. This explosion produces a shockwave and may scatter shrapnel, increasing its destructive radius. Mines can be tailored for various targets, with anti-personnel mines designed to injure or maim individuals, and anti-vehicle mines intended to incapacitate or destroy vehicles.

Deployment and Impact
Deployed strategically, land mines serve both defensive and offensive purposes. They can be hidden below ground, disguised in vegetation, or placed in water, making detection difficult. Their presence forces adversaries to slow their advance or avoid certain areas, altering battle dynamics. However, the impact of land mines extends beyond military aims. Mines left behind after conflicts pose lasting threats to civilians, impacting communities by causing injuries, deaths, and hindering access to land for agriculture or development.

Humanitarian and Legal Aspects
The long-term dangers of land mines have prompted international efforts to ban their use and initiate demining operations. Treaties like the Ottawa Treaty aim to eliminate anti-personnel mines globally, highlighting the humanitarian imperative to prevent further harm. Demining, the process of removing and defusing mines, is labor-intensive and costly, involving both technology and manual efforts to ensure safety. Understanding how land mines work is thus essential not only for military strategy but also for fostering safer, mine-free environments worldwide.

text:
For anyone who is curious, Toro's harness is not on wrong. It's a front clip harness which is meant to help prevent pulling. It was actually very nice of them to put that harness on him for Ryan. There are so many people who expect you to walk a dog that pulls and don't bother to use simple, humane tools like front clip harnesses or head halters. Using these tools makes walks safer for both the dog and the person holding onto them as they will be unable to pull the leash out of the hand or worse, pull someone over.

Also, I DO love you, Toro ü•∞

text:
Im getting back into running now. Just started again yesterday morning after a multi year hiatus. When I was in high school, I was like you. I trained during the summer, but unfortunately during my senior year the new coach developed this thinking that if we all trained together at the same pace we would all work as a team. Well, when your slowest guy can barely break 27 minutes and you're up here trying to break 17's, it's not exactly the best strategy. I think that was the main reason I didnt get my full achievement during my senior year. Track was a different story, but that was because I had motivation from a new coach and I had a good team to compete with. Also, one of the things I believe that kept me from really achieving what I wanted was not having ANY competition until Regionals and State. I trained, but I didnt have that extra push to make it another minute faster because I simply was not running that fast due to not having anyone to run with that was that fast.

I watched your video and I truely believe you are correct. I know during my senior year I didnt run as much as a could have but then I went to college and we were running 10-12 miles per day most of the time. Plus our races were 10k's a lot of times so a 5k seemed like nothing. I remember when I was running there and there was a 5k back home that I attended. Dude, I flat out smoked all of the competition. I actually beat the organizer to where he was supposed to direct people to go. I took the wrong turn because there was an arrow pointing in that direction and ended up running about another mile more than I was supposed to but still beat everyone back. Of course, I didnt accept 1st place because I went the wrong way. The arrow was apparently for a bike-a-thon sometime prior to that race.

Anyway, long story kinda short, I ended up getting burned out through college after running so much. I went straight from CC to indoor track and then to outdoor track with no breaks in between. Constant pushing every day. I needed a break. Break times over folks. 217 pounds later, it's time to get back at it!
